<subSubSection id="690B22FEDAA8FBAB542089A2B5E6DF6E" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7103E3B2AF7F5C58FB64CCCB7C7F7E14" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="890F14EEF11F11F5F0F5D6AB26F5203F" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">
<taxonomicName id="AED6614EC5A69E07377A4346336168CD" authorityName="Vargas &amp; Palacios" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Pero" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pero lopezi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lopezi">
<emphasis id="01E549C58A31C45434C60C3916A62CA5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Pero lopezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recognized by the slightly dentate postmedial line with outwardly rounded teeth on upperside of forewing (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="89FB75DD4A0EAFBA67955E8365FF9870" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Adult stage of Pero lopezi Vargas &amp; Palacios, sp. nov. A. Holotype male in dorsal view; B. Holotype male in ventral view. Scale bar: 1 cm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.54177.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460409" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">1A</figureCitation>
), parallel-sided uncus with round apex and narrow longitudinal subscaphium (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="916BAB4491E6476794F5D4DCC5CC6838" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male genitalia of Pero lopezi Vargas &amp; Palacios, sp. nov. A. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; B. Phallus in lateral view; C. Detail of serrated carina of phallus close to apex. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.54177.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460410" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">2A</figureCitation>
) and phallus with a serrated carina near apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7E97BA785F53C286539A55A22D5A2164" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male genitalia of Pero lopezi Vargas &amp; Palacios, sp. nov. A. Male genitalia in ventral view, phallus removed; B. Phallus in lateral view; C. Detail of serrated carina of phallus close to apex. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.54177.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460410" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">2C</figureCitation>
). The morphology of the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="0EEBD324B03D4EDA8D74A4A63B0B903D" genus="P." lsidName="P. lopezi" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="lopezi">
<emphasis id="6B727AE89397255F2AFCF71EE00E212F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">P. lopezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
allows it to be assigned to Group 15 sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="72F8DBC56FCE7A5C2E0A738E10C6162C" author="Poole, RW" journalOrPublisher="Department of Agriculture" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="1 - 257" refId="B15" refString="Poole, RW, 1987. A taxonomic review of the new world moth genus Pero (Lepidoptera: Geometridae). Technical Bulletin of the U. S. Department of Agriculture 1698: 1 - 257" title="A taxonomic review of the new world moth genus Pero (Lepidoptera: Geometridae). Technical Bulletin of the U. S." volume="1698" year="1987">Poole (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, among which this is remarkably similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="D0260941DAA6D0B180916B706A0B6EAD" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Pero" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pero acopa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acopa">
<emphasis id="7849EDEB8733AD0A62C6887D9C0ED1FE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Pero acopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Poole, 1987. However, 
<taxonomicName id="1DA35C2B1E086746F4C88A59FD3EAE27" genus="P." lsidName="P. lopezi" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="lopezi">
<emphasis id="BD72331A7427750F7A1AD1F0D2E98F0F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">P. lopezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily separable from the species in this group, including 
<taxonomicName id="09EE0748F1DFE89CEFE12C0EECD4CD33" genus="P." lsidName="P. acopa" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="acopa">
<emphasis id="307611D7D50D10890BBDC0BCF0B0D0CB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">P. acopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the slightly dentate postmedial line with outwardly rounded teeth on upperside of forewing, narrow longitudinal subscaphium and phallus with a serrated carina near the apex. Moreover, the antennae of the male in 
<taxonomicName id="B6AF52582642921829ECF52FA1E50AED" genus="P." lsidName="P. acopa" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="acopa">
<emphasis id="86049625238F686B52416F30264B8E1D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">P. acopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are pectinate, but not in 
<taxonomicName id="2AD9C06EFCBD96680E2E680DC6A2E2E1" genus="P." lsidName="P. lopezi" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="lopezi">
<emphasis id="1A51FC845D0AC66AF405BDF17209F216" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">P. lopezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="E7D24ECCFA8EBC3038F3EFA5C22EA4DB" doi="10.3897/nl.43.54177.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460409" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
